segments.text: Oh, another guy I met at that time was Lionel Wilson.
He also came out to the courts.
He's a black student, law student, just fresh out of law school.
And he was married to a redhead.
And lived in the same neighborhood in Oakland.
And I went over to their house, met Dorothy.
And he called me several times to want to play in doubles.
There was a tournament, so we played several doubles in tournaments together.
So he was another one.
And then there was this one psychiatrist who came up.
Yeah, in his second term, the mayor of Oakland.
The mayor of Oakland.
So many of these people have risen to dizzying heights.
When we had the right to call them out, Lionel and Dorothy came down at one of the tournaments.
Yeah.
When I was director of tennis.
Over the last several years, we would bump into him in celebrity tournaments.
And then just recently, Dan is sending the postcard because he's been singing on TV.
Oh, is that right?
Yeah.
Yes, there is.
Oh, when I was marketing director for Brown Construction.
I knew he was mayor, I'd seen his name at the end of the paper.
I'd sent him our packet.
I asked my boss if he thought it was a good lead in case there was any jobs to be done in Oakland, would they want to bid on it?
And he said, yes, go ahead and mail him our packet.
So I used him as a prospect for a construction business that I was making.
But it never hurt.
Let me ask the rest of you.
Let me change the subject for a moment and ask you about your father's efforts to locate you.
You didn't find out about that, of course, until you got hold of your sister.
And then you found out that your father had put ads in the paper, tried to locate you.
Do you have any, what are your feelings about your parents?
How do you think your parents felt?
They knew that you'd escaped.
They were notified, yeah.
How do you think they, because they couldn't reach you either.
No, no.
What do you think they were thinking?
I'm sure he's okay.
He's out there someplace.
We trained him well enough so he could survive.
I hope that's what they thought.
Because my mother kept telling them, my nieces that she was raising, he's not taught.
He's not taught.
And he won't, you know, I think that's another endearing part of my life, in a sense.
That, you know, to have parents...
that cared for me, to look for me.
Sure, sure.
It isn't necessarily the finding, just sometimes, like in life, it's the pursuit of something.
That's the important part, sure.
Of course, it would be ideal if you have the pleasure of pursuit and finding, but it feels good.
And my feeling has always been that I could see what he did was to prepare me for all eventualities, which any father would do, which I would do for every student I ever had.
I would prepare him whatever I teach because I can't be there the rest of his life.
But when I teach somebody to ski, I tell him the color of the snow.
You won't find that in any book that there's
white and there's white.
There's cool white and warm white.
It makes a difference on the drag of your skis.
It might save your life if you go 60 miles an hour and you go over a yellow spot because you're going to go head over tea cattle.
Or the skis will go out from under you if you go over blue.
Right.
And you've got that training soldiers to go to Russia, training
the soldiers on the drill field.
He was preparing them.
You pay $20 and I give you the best backhand in the world.
I think that's an animalistic thing.
You find it amongst the monkeys, the guys that teach the young chimps how to swing from tree to tree.
Their mothers tell them how to eat right and comb their hair.
and stay clean and shape up so that they survive.
Do you have any questions?
Were your dad's efforts to find you extensive?
Did they go on for years?
Yeah, evidently.
And do you know whether he advertised in newspapers in the areas where you were and you just didn't see it, or whether he wasn't in the right location?
I personally think he might have advertised in the San Francisco Chronicle.

that's why i thought maybe herb kane picked up on that item but i that's just i never found it i went to look for it i simply got dizzy looking going back on in those years and i can't got a headache from i tried several hours at the morgue in san francisco to find any mention either of me or
I wasn't looking for the ad at that time, but I would have seen, if I had seen my pictures and my name in Germany, like I saw that on that, I mean, it always jumps the graphics of my name.
What makes you think that it might have been in the San Francisco paper?
Because Lottie told me there were major newspapers that he advertised in.
American newspapers.
American newspapers.
Maybe Los Angeles, or it could have been Los Angeles.
Wire service.
I mean, he could have seen it on a...
I mean, not in the paper itself, like you say, it could have been a rival paper, but they get the same information from the... Just simply ask for the paper.
Yeah, maybe someday I'll ask him if there was an ad in it.
But he wrote that.
But I never thought of running any ads in a German newspaper, since I had given up on Europe, per se.
after I just didn't want to return to Europe.
The only other question I had was a paranoia question.

When you married Jean, I could see the paranoia going in two directions, either getting worse because suddenly you had somebody in collusion with you that didn't know she was in collusion and so you had to worry more, or whether since you decided to become more stable, whether you were able to relax and work that out.
Do you remember what your reaction was very closely on the marriage itself?
I would say...
The feelings would constantly fluctuate between the two.
So both were happening.
Yes.
In fact, that's probably a good way to describe all throughout that period.
The very basic fear and flight.
The constant courage and fear.
press on and hide.
And I've found out that is a very, very basic animalistic trait that we all have.
I've probably had it more than others.
But when I was studying the psychology of a tennis match, how to get yourself into a proper thing, you have to...
wait till you get rid of your fear before you can make any kind of a good shot.
Because as soon as the fear creeps into your body, the chemistry, like that match that I lost, that there's no way you cannot, that thing is just like concrete.
You've heard of the expression, the frozen elbow or the concrete elbow.
And it isn't just, you know, it probably was stronger than me.
And it kept going back and forth and back and forth.
But it's not unusual.
And I don't know what I'd done if it wasn't there all the time.
It must be nice, I guess.
You don't have to... Well, everybody has secrets.
Everybody has...
I don't want you to think that you...
lived a relationship that nobody else experiences.
That's what I finally learned.
Everybody experiences those things.
That's what I finally learned.
Just maybe the degree is different.
Or the cues.
You would suspect the cues sooner than I would.
If you were starting to be asked questions, your defenses would go up a lot earlier than mine.
Mine would go up too, and I think most men would, to being asked certain questions.
But I think yours would go up sooner than mine.
Gene, can I ask you a couple questions?
Can I ask you to change places for a minute?
Let me ask again what you thought when you were being rebuffed at these various points.
I mean, there has to be... You're married to a man, all right, the marriage...
You met at the dance.
You got married in October.
But still, you're dealing with somebody who's almost a cardboard figure on occasion.
In the earliest stages of it,
I really wasn't too concerned about...
I didn't have that many questions.
My primary concerns were about his health.
If you're marrying somebody, you want to be pretty comfortable with their health, and he looked very robust.
I worked for an insurance company at that time, and
I urged him to go get an annual physical the first year we were married.
He did do that.
We were on the employee benefit plan.
The doctor's report came back through my office, kind of a conflict of interest situation to say the least.
Professionally, I deal with it.

the claims coming in and it was my own husband and I felt like a lawyer in a sense reading his medical report but on the other hand I'm concerned about it because he was virtually a stranger when I married him.
We had known each other for a long time.
Nothing of his background and at that point in time I found out about his pneumonia.
He'd never mentioned that and in his history whatever he did to the doctor showed up as an old
some kind of old inflammatory changes in his lungs.
So I called up the doctor and I explained to him this kind of dilemma that I was in.
New bride, here's this information, and the doctor said, oh, don't worry about that.
He said, your husband is basically a very healthy fellow.
So I thought, okay, that's all I really need to know.
I never told him that I had seen his medical report.
You knew she had?
But that's why he stalled for going to the doctor.
I know how these things...
Anyway, that kind of question.
She is asking me to take an examination.
She tells me to go see the doctor.
The doctor is going to report to her.
So you suspected that you were being put up to it.
That's why I stalled.
Were you being put up to it?
Did you really want to see that report?
No.
Actually, I was very taken aback when the report came through.
It didn't necessarily have to come through, but it happened to do.
Okay, so that answered the basic questions.
Could that report have...
What I'm trying to respond to is when you said, what kind of questions did I have and how did I feel when I didn't get an answer?
Okay, so the basic question was answered.
He was healthy.
Now I don't want to know, I don't want to pry about where did he get these things, changes in his life.
He was healthy.
In terms of the current reality, everything was okay.
Let's not bother about the rest of it.
So then, those early years of our marriage, very seldom did questions come up about any past history.
And in my perception of things during those subsequent years and the next six, seven, eight years, whatever,
very little came up in the way of necessity to threaten him about going before any kind of authorities.

I was the front person in most all of our dealings, which was very easy for me to do because I was up to that point anyway, take care of all the financial returns, take care of all the practicalities.
If we bought property, I filled out the forms.
Faster for me to do that.
He was busy with his job or whatever it was.
I had access to telephone.
So it just was kind of a natural thing to do, to fall into it.
doing all of those things and then to skip way ahead when the time came then many years later for me to

Well, I guess the best way I can phrase it is after many, many years of doing all of that for the whole family, and then the kids are gone, and then later on they're just the two of us, I became exhausted, sick and tired of doing all the tax work and all this stuff.
And then I would put him in situations where...
Why doesn't he go do it?
And he wouldn't do it.
So then my feeling of being, I was just, I'm just used up.
I'm just, why won't you do it?
Then came the hard questions.
And the same in the areas of the emotionality about things.
I think my perception was that he had used my emotionality about all of these other things.
He didn't have to reveal.

how or get caught in any kinds of traps about displays of emotions or he was you know just and I'm all this and I was just used up so now hard questions have to come how come you don't want to do this why don't you do that and not getting a satisfactory like you use in cardboard response so there was a lot of years when there was no confrontation about any of it

by uncertainty yeah yeah uh did you begin to notice a breakdown of of uh defenses it seems to me i'm getting the feeling that we're repressed i'm getting the feeling that uh it was uh that dennis's defenses were either breaking down or showing you light in between them somehow
that would encourage you to ask more, to demand more.

It sounds as if he was almost saying, press a little harder and maybe we'll... That he was trying to cooperate on the inside, and you were trying to get to it on the outside, but that this wall that had been built up over years prevented you both from touching each other.
That's quite possible.
I think just in general terms, people get locked into whatever roles and responsibilities that sort of...
sometimes by default.
A lot of his responses to my behavior fit very well into this, because I was used to be the aggressive one, the business woman, and whether he even offered to do it, he may not have had a chance to.
I might have just done it anyway.
But you don't see a point at which it was starting to become that you sensed that he was trying to cooperate from the inside,

Well, I thought that we always discussed these difficult matters, and that the fact that you actually went ahead and did it, like the actual, like the phoning and the setting up of the appointments and so on,
I think that came much later in our marriage.
I tried to be as supportive as I could in other ways, other than the actual doing of it.
And obviously there was a lot of other kinds of...
It's not anything that I enjoyed.
That's a very bad part of being a...
You're not a whole person.
You're lucky.
You try to be as whole as you can.
I was trying to be as whole as I could.
And the rest, like if I was three-quarter whole, I felt, well, that's me.
The best you can ask for.
The best you can hope for.
That's the best I can ask for.
And not to...
well over the last quarter when you got three quarters and then later on i got more compassionate when i heard you read enough about the other unfortunate people and of course three quarters
And my basic approach to that was, I'd say it to myself, you can only get so much, whatever is there of the person is all you can get.
If there isn't any more, you will not get any more.
Maybe he's just dull.
Maybe that's all there was.
Maybe he's dull.
And I accepted that because he was such a good person, and I've said that in so many ways to so many people.

his basic integrity his goodness all of those kinds of things you know he's kind he's all these other things so if there was if there was only this kind of level of affect coming maybe that's okay and i would have to deal with whatever might end up being deficiencies to me i'd have to deal with it in some other manner and that was okay for a long time but then it wasn't anymore what changed it
I think I indicated there were several crises in my life going on.
In her life?
In my life.
I felt like I was just going to be used.
I was used up.
Where did you find Dr. Bernstein's name, Mark Bernstein?
No, we belonged to, as part of my benefit package.
I have a health plan with one of the major clinics in Honolulu.
And he was one of the staff psychiatrists.
What building?
A major building down south?
So it's called Straub Clinic.
It's a big clinic on South King Street in Honolulu.
Straub Clinic.
S-T-R-U-B.
Tell me what, when you finally
When the final crisis finally came, 1980, summer of 80, you have both seen Dr. Bernstein?
No, no.
We didn't see him until about September.
Oh, wait a minute.
Then I have the chronology wrong.
I'm saying in the summer of 80, when I found out about Cheryl and I came back from Colorado,
I was already set for the retirement.
Yes.
And come to, you know, whatever anxieties you go through on a career change.
And when I came back from that, and I had been in a depressive kind of phase for, well, maybe a year and a half to that time, but, you know, functional.
Yeah.
Go to work and do all those things.
Sure.
I've done it.
And when I came back from that, I had no energy left.
That's just it.
So I went on that basis.
to Dr. Bernstein and kind of got him involved, come in and help me out, you know.
So you were going about the summer of 80 to Dr. Bernstein?
September of 81, this is.
September of 81?
Yeah, I'm sorry, I'm not sure.
No problem.
September of 81, you started going to Dr. Bernstein?
Mm-hmm.
And how long before you could get Dennis into it?
fairly soon after that a couple of two or three sessions as i recall well he didn't hang back and how did you respond then as to uh dr bernstein's
probing.
You said that it had a major impact, even though you didn't tell anybody.
Yeah, it did.
It seemed to have been amazing.
I didn't really think much of these psychiatrists' methods, but I guess they do work.
They do open up things, and of course they're quite painful.
They break down these walls that you build up.
But it's...
It's hard to leave, but then you do manage to survive, and then probably are better for it, because you've broken down some walls, maybe, and that's, you now have a bigger room.
Somehow that seems to make it work.
About how long did you go?
From September to February.
No, September to about January.
Once a week or so.
Then Dennis stopped going.
He didn't want to be changed.
This now, you remind me, you said, you know, what caused the final kind of thing, and I had said something about I figured this was the end, there wasn't going to be any more change.
He had told me in absolute terms, as far as I was hearing, that he would not go back to Dr. Bernstein anymore.
He felt that he was perfectly alright and there was no reason, he wasn't going to be changed anymore.
And I remember this one session I went into, Dr. Bernstein and I, you know, I was coming on my own.
There was no more of this marital counseling.
It was just going to be, which, you know, so I needed it anyway, but okay.
It wasn't what I had in mind.
And I remember Dr. Bernstein looking at his records and he said, well, let's see now.
You have only on your medical plan, you have two more visits, something like that.
I just thought, oh,
And I finished the session and I'll go to the office.
I'm never going to go back either.

He was about, at that point, about the, I considered my last friend, if you will, the only one in the world I had left that would be concerned enough about me to, for any reason, and he's putting a price tag on it, which, I mean, in reality, of course, there is, but I don't need that.
All the rest of this, I certainly can endow along with it, so I just wasn't going to go back.
And then that's about
within the next week or so came our final separation kind of scene and then as I mentioned to you then after that
There's this relief, kind of all these, you know, floods of emotions, and kind of being able to come together on that.
And then I went back one more time to tell Dr. Bernstein what had happened and what the story then was, and then that's the rest of it.
So that was about January, February, March of...
It was two years ago.
I've been in 82.
March of 82, we're there about March, April 82.
Mm-hmm.
In March 1982, tell me what the home, what your house looked like.
You were living on the 12th floor.
In the Hawaiian Princess.
The Hawaiian Princess.
It's a condominium complex?
Condominium.
Lahi Lahi Point.
Lahi Lahi.
Lahi Lahi Point, where Prince Makaha would dive off to meet his amakua, the shark.
I see.
I see.
L-A-H-A, Lahi Lahi?
Lahi Lahi.
L-A-H-I.
L-A-H-I.
L-A-H-I.
I see.
And it was a beautiful home.
I get the feeling of a balcony three-quarters of the way around the...
It had a wraparound lanai, call it.
Lanai?
Lanai, L-A-N-A-I-N-A-I-N-A-I.
And at that moment, you were still working for Mutual of New York?
No, no.
Oh.
That was, I was working for Hawaii Refugee Resettlement Agency.
Got it.
It was the fairly new, fairly new executive at that time.
How far from work were you?
About 30 miles out.
And you had to go into downtown Hawaii?
Mm-hmm.
Mm-hmm.
And when did you take that job?
How much earlier did you just take that job?
In November of 81, so I'd only been working there for four months.
How old was your brother?
Sixteen.
Twelve.
Good, good.
Can you think of anything since it is... Five minutes.
Two minutes before two.
I wanted to ask you if it would be at all helpful or...
Any reason that you might want to talk to Cheryl or Mark about anything?
Their recollections of anything?
Well, my... Perhaps we can talk even later on.
We don't have to do it at this moment.
Because our memories, you know, sometimes...
I'm curious what the kids thought of Dennis, and I'm curious whether they saw in him
survival techniques that they should have benefited by or that seemed odd to them in the United States?
Well, they perfectly are.
I'm sure they'd be delighted to talk about it.
That's nice.
And the book is going on?
Yes.
Good.
I know you mentioned Cheryl had not only a bad time with her health.
How is her health ultimately?
She seems fine now.
She had the two year, supposed to be checked every six months for two years.
She passed her two years exam.
But then in June, it's now a half year later, two and a half years later, she said no sign of recurrence.
But the ugly part about melanoma is that it could be years.
Well, we're all in the same boat.
No one knows whether we're not going to fall down outside.
You know, life goes on as usual, and she's very healthy.
all the problems are going to be taken care of eventually.
It could happen in a traffic accident.
And so there was always the chance that I didn't have to make any decision.
The confrontation would never come.
Yes, you could just keep putting the confrontation off until the guy with the scythe comes across.
And Cheryl...
You said also had a difficult emotional time trying to commit suicide?
Well, she didn't know over to act, but it got, she threatened it.
Oh, I see.
When we were going off on our, going off to get married, just, you know, lip service.
Okay, okay.
I thought it was something much more serious.
They always thought, including Jean, that I was the perfect, perfect mate for Jean because
She's a very, I don't know what the terminology is, but with her, what you might call wild ideas of running and moving and dropping out and going out in the blaze and not really meaning any of this.
But I don't know.
Nobody knows for sure.
But it's constantly being threatened, you know.
And all the vendettas would just stand there and sip this martini and smile, you see.
And they said, you know, there's like an anchor.
You know, here are these people all going to shoot up.
You know what Cheryl said to us?
When we left the other day, Cheryl was sitting down.
She said, Mom, you know...
I'm really feeling kind of a struggle now.
I'm feeling this sort of role reversal.
Should you always think that your parents are going to be some kind of stability?
And I never was, and now I'm the only stable one.
She says, I have a home and a family here, and I'm really trying hard to get my head together.
And she said, I just wish I had, sometimes I wish I had normal parents.
And then she looked kind of chagrined.
Let me ask you about the period when you were drinking a lot.
Is it brought about by these same problems, or just boredom, or it's not important?
Oh, well, when we live in California, we're just like the affluent society.
Everybody had their martinis, and after a while, I had
Actually, gin makes me a little ill.
So then we switched to vodka.
Our friends had martinis.
As you get older, then everybody's kind of... We got together, everybody.
Martinis, steaks, and salads was the thing.
And fortunately, neither one of us can drink after we eat.
So it's all over with by 8 o'clock.
You know, you have a couple of cocktails before dinner.
We enjoy wine.
And then that's it.
But it's, you know, when I say a lot, every night is a lot, if you don't hear that.
But as far as having a...
I should kind of briefly mention that name, Alice McIntyre.
Oh, she stood up for us at our wedding.
She stood up for us at the wedding, and she was one of the really brightest women I have ever had the pleasure of being with.
She was the office manager for Clark Door Company, an absolute savior as a backup for my work.
She would straighten out all the billing and all the complaints while I was out on the road.
So influential is what you're saying?

just incredible i haven't had one since like that but the drinking was not uh a period we'd get together with them it was it was never to the point that we were ever not functioning right or that it became evidently of some concern but not nothing um a concern as we got older from a health standpoint yeah you start reading you know gee maybe we shouldn't drink this actually it diminishes or it
Your mineral supply gets diminished.
All these kinds of things.
Sex drive hasn't helped a lot either.
Well, I'm sure that's understandable.
How do you see Dennis?
If you were telling a close girlfriend, and it doesn't have to be honest,
You're going to see all these things before they ever get to the point where...
I'm not worried about that.
I mean, I'm either going to be upfront about it or I'm not going to say it at all.
How do you see Dennis?
If you were describing Dennis to a close girlfriend or to your mother, if you would...
very close, you would say?
My very first and foremost reaction is I have always considered him a very substantial person.
That's extremely important to me, is a feeling of substance about somebody I can really get a big arm for.
He's really...
Despite the fact that you feel that you took over a lot of responsibility?
Mm-hmm.
Mm-hmm.
the part that made me angry was not that he, I didn't think he couldn't do it, that he didn't have the mental capacity or the imagination, whatever, but he wouldn't do it for

I could never come to terms with the reasons, the discrepancy between, I think I mentioned that earlier, his aggressiveness in many, many other arenas, like sports, for example, to see him come down the face of Squaw Peak and all these kind of things, and yet this hanging back and, you know, like...
More pablum, more pablum, in so many other areas.
And, of course, by contrast, which I would need to bring out, my own father, who was not this stature, but who was such a substantial type person in terms of the taking care part of his family,
And my mother is blithering.
And my dad would always put down the dollar bills on the table every day for the food and tell her this, and you're going to do this, and this, and this.
And the life was like all laid out.
And so the confusion then for me of seeing Dennis be so aggressive in many, many other areas, but not everything that kind of happened.
Which now I can...
You know, putting pieces together diminishes much of the anger.
Oh, yes, I'll bet it will.
Have you anything to ask?
I'm sure I'll think of something between now and the next.
